A matching CSS snippet will make digital viewing effortless while preserving the calm aesthetic and accessibility.  
Here’s a compact, standards‑friendly version you can paste into the `<style>` section of any webpage or into a Markdown stylesheet:

```css
/* 🕊 Supportive‑Dialogue Quick Reference — Accessible Theme */

:root {
  --primary-accent: #2E4B6B;
  --secondary-accent: #0B6F8E;
  --neutral-bg: #FAFAFA;
  --text-color: #1E1E1E;
  --calm-green: #4F7F5A;
  --caution-amber: #B08F2F;
  --heading-font: "Lato", "Source Sans Pro", sans-serif;
  --body-font: "Merriweather", Georgia, serif;
}

/* Basic layout */
body {
  background: var(--neutral-bg);
  color: var(--text-color);
  font-family: var(--body-font);
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.45;
  margin: 2em auto;
  max-width: 800px;
  padding: 0 1em;
}

/* Headings */
h1, h2, h3 {
  font-family: var(--heading-font);
  color: var(--primary-accent);
  font-weight: 600;
  margin-top: 1.5em;
  margin-bottom: 0.5em;
}

/* Links and accents */
a {
  color: var(--secondary-accent);
  text-decoration: none;
}
a:hover {
  text-decoration: underline;
}

/* Tables */
table {
  width: 100%;
  border-collapse: collapse;
  margin: 1em 0;
  font-size: 0.95rem;
}
th, td {
  border: 1px solid #DDD;
  padding: 0.6em;
}
th {
  background: #F0F0F0;
  color: var(--primary-accent);
}
tr:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #F8F8F8;
}

/* Footer / crisis notice */
footer {
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  color: var(--text-color);
  border-top: 2px solid var(--caution-amber);
  margin-top: 2em;
  padding-top: 1em;
}

/* Optional accent examples */
.success {
  color: var(--calm-green);
}
.warning {
  color: var(--caution-amber);
  font-weight: 600;
}
```

This keeps headings prominent, text readable, and tables soft‑edged. It meets basic WCAG contrast levels and prints clearly if you apply a white background.  

